11. Interview Explanation (30–60 sec)

> A brute-force solution generates all subsets and checks their sums, which takes . The optimization is that we only care about the subset sum modulo k, not the exact sum. Since there are only k possible remainders, we maintain a DP array where dp[r] indicates whether some non-empty subset has remainder r. For each number, we update the reachable remainders using (oldRemainder + num) % k. If remainder 0 becomes reachable, we have found a valid subset. This reduces the complexity to O(n × k) with O(k) extra space.




---

12. Key Takeaways

Brute force explores every subset.

Only the remainder modulo k matters.

DP state represents reachable remainders.

Always update using a copy (new_dp) to avoid reusing the same element multiple times.

Time complexity improves from exponential to polynomial.



---

13. Common Mistakes

❌ Forgetting that the subset must be non-empty.

❌ Updating dp directly instead of using new_dp, which allows the same element to be counted multiple times.

❌ Storing complete sums instead of modulo values, increasing memory and time unnecessarily.

❌ Forgetting to mark the current element alone:

new_dp[num % k] = True

❌ Returning False before processing all elements.


